 of social and political upheaval. Investigating works such as Coleridge's Rime of the Ancient Mariner, Dorothy Wordsworth's Grasmere Journals, and Percy Shelley's Triumph of Life alongside Schelling's unfinished Ages of the World and Schlegel's Athenaeum Fragments, Fay demonstrates how Romantic immanence, despite going largely unrecognized with the loss of its initial context, remains vividly present in these works.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism2DLC. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism2DLC. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aImmanence (Philosophy) in literature2DLC. 0aImmanence (Philosophy) in literature. 0aOther (Philosophy) in literature2DLC. 0aOther (Philosophy) in literature. 0aRomanticismzGreat Britain2DLC. 0aRomanticismzGreat Britain. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Nineteenth-Century Studies. 4aLiterature : Romanticism. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849476040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438494760423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438494760/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles